# WHAT IT IS
#   substudy is "language-learning tools for working with
#   parallel, bilingual subtitles and media files".  It bundles
#   a complete pipeline for studying foreign languages from
#   movies and TV shows:  clean SRT files of non-dialog noise
#   (`clean`), combine a foreign + native subtitle pair into a
#   single bilingual SRT (`combine`), export Anki flashcards
#   from video + bilingual subs (`export anki` via the
#   AnkiConnect plugin), transcribe audio with Whisper /
#   OpenAI to recover lost subtitles (`transcribe`, supporting
#   --related-text / --expected-text priming + multiple output
#   formats), translate foreign subs into the user's native
#   language via OpenAI (`translate`), and list information
#   about files (`list`).  Import from Whisper JSON is also
#   supported (`import whisper-json`).
#
# CLI ARGUMENT GRAMMAR  (verbatim from substudy/src/main.rs
#                       `enum Args` — clap derive)
#   substudy <SUBCOMMAND> [args...]
#
#   Subcommands:
#     clean <SUBS>                   Clean a subtitle file
#                                    (remove non-dialog text)
#
#     combine <FOREIGN_SUBS> <NATIVE_SUBS>
#                                    Combine two subtitle files
#                                    into a single bilingual
#                                    SRT
#
#     export <FORMAT>                Export in one of several
#                                    formats (anki, music
#                                    tracks, etc.)
#       anki <VIDEO> <FOREIGN_SUBS> [<NATIVE_SUBS>] [...flags]
#                                    Anki cards via AnkiConnect
#                                    plugin
#
#     import <FORMAT>                Import in one of several
#                                    formats
#       whisper-json <FILE>            Whisper verbose-JSON
#                                    output
#
#     list <KIND>                    List info about a file
#
#     transcribe <VIDEO>             Transcribe subtitles from
#                                    audio via OpenAI Whisper
#       --related-text <PATH>          Priming text similar to
#                                      the video (cannot be
#                                      combined with
#                                      --expected-text)
#       --expected-text <PATH>         Full expected text (cannot
#                                      be combined with
#                                      --related-text);  best
#                                      for lyrics-based videos
#       --lang <CODE>                  Primary language code
#                                      (e.g. en, es, fr)
#       --format <FORMAT>              Output format
#                                      (srt | whisper-srt |
#                                       whisper-json)
#                                      [default: srt]
#
#     translate <FOREIGN_SUBS>       Translate subtitles via
#                                    OpenAI
#       --foreign-lang <CODE>          Source language code
#                                      (auto-detect if omitted)
#       --native-lang <CODE>           Target language code
#                                      (REQUIRED)
#
#   Standard clap auto-flags:
#     -h, --help                     Show help
#     -V, --version                  Show version
#
# AXIS / CORPUS POSITION
#   Direct dependency on `async-openai = { git = "https://
#   github.com/emk/async-openai.git", branch =
#   "transcription_verbose_json" }` declared in substudy/
#   Cargo.toml — `async-openai` is THE canonical Rust OpenAI
#   SDK maintained by 64bit (64bit/async-openai, 1.6K+ stars;
#   the predominant tokio-async OpenAI client used by every
#   major Rust AI tool — aichat, llm, lumen, cai, mevlog,
#   etc.).  async-openai exposes the typed `Client` constructor
#   with `Client::new()`, `Client::with_config(...)` for
#   custom-base-URL / proxy / auth configurations, the
#   `client.chat()` typed chat-completions API with
#   `CreateChatCompletionRequest`, the `client.completions()`
#   legacy completions API, `client.embeddings()`, `client.
#   images()`, `client.files()`, `client.fine_tuning()`, `client.
#   assistants()`, `client.threads()`, `client.runs()`, `client.
#   audio()` (transcription, translation, TTS), `client.
#   moderations()`, `client.batches()`, `client.models()`, plus
#   every typed request + response struct generated from the
#   OpenAI OpenAPI spec, the `OPENAI_API_KEY` env-var loader,
#   automatic retries via `tower::ServiceBuilder`, server-sent-
#   events streaming for chat completions, and full
#   Azure OpenAI service compatibility via
#   `azure_openai_config()`.  substudy's `src/services/oai.rs`
#   uses `client.audio().transcribe(CreateTranscriptionRequest
#   {...})` for Whisper-driven subtitle generation and
#   `client.chat().create(...)` for the typed `translate`
#   subcommand.  The forked branch
#   `transcription_verbose_json` adds the verbose-json response
#   format required for word-timestamp output.  Verified via:
#     gh api repos/emk/subtitles-rs/contents/substudy/
#         Cargo.toml
#       → async-openai = { git = "https://github.com/emk/
#           async-openai.git", branch =
